Hi Turner,

Thank you for the additional clarification, and my apologies for the initia=
l misunderstanding of your requirements. I can see now you're looking to co=
nnect both a frontend and a backend project to a single domain.

To clarify, it is not possible to assign the same production domain (e.g., =
ria-hunter.app) to two different Vercel projects directly. This is to avoid=
 ambiguity when resolving the domain. However, there are two common approac=
hes you can take to achieve your goal.

Use a Subdomain for the Backend Project: You can create and assign a separa=
te subdomain (for example, api.ria-hunter.app or backend.ria-hunter.app) to=
 your RIA-Hunter (backend) project. Then, you would update the environment =
variables in your RIA-Hunter-app (frontend) project to make API requests to=
 this new subdomain. You can find instructions on how to add a domain in ou=
r documentation on Adding & Configuring a Custom Domain.

Use Next.js Rewrites: A second option is to keep the custom domain ria-hunt=
er.app on your frontend project (RIA-Hunter-app) and use the rewrites featu=
re in your next.config.js file. This would allow you to proxy requests from=
 a specific path (e.g., /api/:path*) on your custom domain to your backend =
project's Vercel URL (ria-hunter.vercel.app). This is a powerful feature th=
at makes it appear as though both services are running on the same domain. =
For more details on this approach, please see our guide on How to serve mul=
tiple projects under a single domain.

You would add the following to the next.config.ts file of your frontend pro=
ject (RIA-Hunter-app):


import type { NextConfig } from 'next'

const nextConfig: NextConfig =3D {
  async rewrites() {
    return [
      {
        // The source path on your frontend project
        source: '/api/:path*',
        // The destination URL of your backend project
        destination: 'https://ria-hunter.vercel.app/api/:path*',
      },
    ]
  },
}

export default nextConfig

With this configuration, any request to ria-hunter.app/api/... will be tran=
sparently proxied to your backend project at ria-hunter.vercel.app/api/....

Both are valid options, and the best choice depends on your specific archit=
ecture. Please let me know if you have any further questions.

